                <h1 class="detailed-view-card-heading">charminar</h1>
                <p class="detailed-view-card-description">The Charminar is an iconic 16th-century monument and mosque in Hyderabad, India, built by Sultan Muhammad Quli Qutb Shah to commemorate the eradication of a deadly plague. Known as the "Four Towers" in Urdu, the structure features four grand arches facing the cardinal directions and is supported by four ornate, 56-meter-tall minarets. Constructed from granite and lime mortar, the Charminar is a symbol of the city's rich culture and history and is a popular global tourist destination.</p>
